ning and Development, a comprehensive overview of planning issues at the time of the First World War. Rediscovering Thomas Adams reintroduces a new generation to a text that quickly became a touchstone for planners and planning in Canada. Updated with commentaries by the country's leading planners who hold up Adams' text as a mirror to reflect upon contemporary planning issues, this richly illustrated book highlights Adams' influence on the planning profession and the continued significance of his comprehensive and pragmatic vision for building better rural and urban communities. First published in 1917, Rural Planning and Development continues to resonate as a broad vision for planning, one that moves beyond the demands of the moment to offer a long-term vision for a better future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDéveloppement ruralxCanada. 0aRural developmentxCanada. 0aRural developmentzCanada. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh1 aCaldwell, Wayne J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Wayne J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCameron, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarnegie, Colonel David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeymour, H.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481925140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774819251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.